communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

["Peste des petits ruminants (PPR), also known as sheep and goat plague, is a highly contagious animal disease affecting small ruminants. Once introduced, the virus can infect up to 90 per cent of an animal heard, and the disease kills anywhere from 30 to 70 per cent of infected animals. The PPR virus does not infect humans.

"FAO [Food and Agriculture Organization of the United Nations] and the World Organisation for Animal Health (OIE) are mobilizing the international community around a new global initiative: the fight to eradicate PPR by 2030. FAO's ultimate goal is to facilitate the eradication PPR and to sustainably improve small ruminant production in order to benefit food and nutrition security and strengthen the livelihood resilience of rural women and men." (http://www.fao.org/ppr/en/)

An FAO-OIE Global Conference on Peste des Petits Ruminants will be held 6-7 Sep 2018, in Brussels, Belgium. See information at http://www.fao.org/ppr/globalconference/en/.

Additional information is available at the OIE and FAO Peste des petits ruminants portals at http://www.oie.int/en/animal-health-in-the-world/ppr-portal/ and http://www.fao.org/ppr/en/, respectively. - Mod.CRD

HealthMap/ProMED-mail map of Kenema, Eastern Province, Sierra Leone: https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=5957821,15860.]
